Thanks!

Okay, thanks!

Can you check this in your layout script:
{code}var_dump($this->getHelper('navigation')->findHelper('menu', false));{code}


Please use the code tags in your comments. Thanks!{noformat}{code}Insert code here{code}{noformat}

With ZF 1.12 that is:

{code}null{code}


With ZF 1.11.10 I do get the helper

All my applications works fine with 1.12!

Please check outside your application:
{code}
// Auto loader
require_once 'Zend/Loader/Autoloader.php';
Zend_Loader_Autoloader::getInstance();

// View
$view = new Zend_View();

// Container
$container = new Zend_Navigation(
    array(
        array(
            'label' => 'Home',
            'uri'   => 'home',
        ),
    )
);

echo $view->navigation($container)->menu();
{code}

Okay, fine!

Now you can check this in your application. (Put it at the end of your layout script!)
{code}
$this->setHelperPath(null);
var_dump($this->getHelper('navigation')->findHelper('menu', false));
{code}

{quote}Am I correct in understanding that a fix to some added functionality previous to 1.12 was lost in 1.11?{quote}
Yes, in old versions your own navigation helpers could not have the name "menu" or "breadcrumbs".

{quote}Perhaps off-topic but the reason I use Zym is mainly to directly access the view in a view helper.{quote}
Your view helper must extends {{Zend_View_Helper_Abstract}} and then you can use {{$this->view}} inside the helper. The abstract class was added in version 1.6.0.
